          "body": "The chapter's only sustained imperatives arrive in 6:18-20. *Flee immorality* (pheugete) — present tense, continuous flight, no negotiation. Paul gives the unique reason: every other sin is *outside the body*, but sexual sin is *against one's own body* (6:18). The exact sense is debated — Paul may mean sexual sin is uniquely self-targeting because it weds the offender to the partner, or because it desecrates the very temple the Spirit indwells. Verse 19 unveils the temple language explicitly: your body is a *naos* (inner sanctuary) of the Holy Spirit. The shekinah no longer dwells behind a curtain in Jerusalem; it dwells in the embodied believer. And the body that houses the Spirit is itself owned property — bought (*agorazo*) at a price (*time*). The chapter ends not in prohibition but in doxology: *glorify God in your body* (6:20). The body is the venue of worship, not the obstacle to it."
